<Layout title="Section 7 – Oxygenation">
  <h1>Section 7: Oxygenation</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.7 – Demonstrates Oxygenation Techniques</em></p>
  <p>
    Identify assessment findings for oxygenation, ventilation, and gas exchange. Describe
    and perform common nursing interventions including oxygen administration and suctioning.
  </p>

  <h2>Respiratory Assessment</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Rate:</strong> 12–20 breaths/min (adult normal); tachypnea &gt; 20; bradypnea &lt; 12.</li>
    <li><strong>Depth &amp; rhythm:</strong> Regular, equal bilateral expansion; use of accessory muscles indicates distress.</li>
    <li><strong>Breath sounds:</strong> Vesicular (normal periphery), bronchovesicular (major airways), bronchial (trachea).</li>
    <li><strong>Adventitious sounds:</strong> Crackles (fluid/secretions), wheezes (bronchospasm), rhonchi (large airway secretions), stridor (upper airway obstruction), pleural friction rub.</li>
    <li><strong>SpO₂:</strong> Normal 95–100%; &lt; 90% requires urgent intervention.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Structures &amp; Functions of the Respiratory System</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Upper airway: Nose/mouth → pharynx → larynx — warms, humidifies, filters air.</li>
    <li>Lower airway: Trachea → bronchi → bronchioles → alveoli — site of gas exchange.</li>
    <li>Alveoli: Oxygen diffuses into capillaries; CO₂ diffuses out — driven by concentration gradients.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Oxygen Delivery Systems</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Device</th><th>Flow Rate</th><th>FiO₂ Delivered</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Nasal cannula</td><td>1–6 L/min</td><td>24–44%</td><td>Comfortable for long-term use; FiO₂ increases ~4% per L/min</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Simple face mask</td><td>6–10 L/min</td><td>35–55%</td><td>Minimum 6 L/min to prevent CO₂ rebreathing</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Partial rebreather mask</td><td>8–15 L/min</td><td>50–70%</td><td>Reservoir bag must remain inflated; 1/3 of bag exhaled air returned</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Non-rebreather mask</td><td>10–15 L/min</td><td>60–90%</td><td>One-way valves; highest non-invasive FiO₂; keep bag inflated</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Venturi mask</td><td>Varies</td><td>24–50% (precise)</td><td>Best for COPD patients requiring controlled O₂</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ COPD Caution</strong>
    Patients with chronic hypercapnia (COPD) may rely on hypoxic drive. Target SpO₂ 88–92%
    to avoid suppressing respiratory drive. Use Venturi mask for precise delivery.
  </div>

  <h2>Oxygen Safety</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Oxygen supports combustion — keep away from flames, sparks, and smoking.</li>
    <li>Post "Oxygen In Use" and "No Smoking" signs.</li>
    <li>Store tanks secured and upright; never store near heat sources.</li>
    <li>Check O₂ levels before use; ensure adequate supply.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Airway Management &amp; Suctioning</h2>
  <h3>Maintaining an Airway</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Positioning:</strong> Head-tilt chin-lift or jaw thrust for unconscious patients.</li>
    <li><strong>Oral airway (OPA):</strong> Use in unconscious patients without gag reflex; prevents tongue from occluding airway.</li>
    <li><strong>Nasopharyngeal airway (NPA):</strong> Use when OPA is contraindicated; tolerated in semi-conscious patients.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Oropharyngeal Suctioning</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Indicated when patient cannot clear secretions independently.</li>
    <li>Use Yankauer suction catheter for oropharyngeal suctioning.</li>
    <li>Apply suction only while withdrawing the catheter; suction for no more than 10–15 seconds at a time.</li>
    <li>Allow 30 seconds to 1 minute between suction passes; pre-oxygenate if needed.</li>
    <li>Assess breath sounds and SpO₂ before and after suctioning.</li>
  </ul>

